# World Files / Saves / Distribution

Worlds should probably be treated more like documents than like internal app
state. Saves are also files of course, just a different kind. A world is the
definition/template, a save is a playthrough.

I still think the app can have a worlds menu / recent worlds / maybe a worlds
dir, but the important part is that a world should be a thing a user can move
around, share, rename, back up etc without it feeling like they are poking at
app internals.

So:

- world file: portable world definition
- save file: one run through a world, including images etc

`New world` should not open a file picker first. It should just open the editor.
The file path should only matter on save.

`Start game` should usually happen from a selected/opened world, not from a
file picker.

`Open world...` / `Open save...` are the places where file dialogs make sense.

If a remembered/recent world got moved, it should just show up as missing.
Then there can be a `Locate file...` option etc. No need to be overly clever
about it.

There is also the portable / easy-customization idea:

- binary
- config next to it
- worlds dir next to it

Then a "bundle" is basically just such a directory zipped up. That is actually
quite nice. But it should probably be a portable mode, not the only mode. If
there is config/data next to the executable, use that. Otherwise use the normal
OS data/config dirs.

# World Name / File Name

The displayed world name should not come from the file name. That feels wrong.
I don't want `cyber_runner` to be the displayed title just because that is a
reasonable file name.

The world title should be stored in the file and displayed from there.

The file name can still be derived from the title by default. That part is
fine. But then on rename, the file should usually also get renamed, instead of
the current behavior where changing the title effectively creates a new file
and leaves the old one behind.

Probably:

- title is the canonical displayed name
- filename/slug is derived from it by default
- when editing an existing world and the title changes, also rename the file
- if that would conflict, ask what to do instead of silently overwriting

Might make sense to only auto-rename if the current file name still matches the
old derived slug. That way we don't fight a user who intentionally chose some
different file name.

# World Structure / Variants / Blocks

The current "character section" model is too weak for what I actually use it
for. I often abuse it to create subvariants that differ in more than just the
player character.

There are also chunks of the world description that I want in many variants,
but not all. Right now the bad options are:

- keep them in the main description and tell the model to ignore them in some
  character sections
- or duplicate the same text into all relevant sections

Both are bad in different ways.

I think the better model is to stop pretending these are just character
sections and make the structure explicit:

- world blocks: reusable chunks of description
- variants: named setups / subvariants that include some blocks and add their
  own text
- player characters: actual character descriptions/start states

Then a variant could select which main blocks are active, instead of forcing
manual duplication or "ignore this" prose hacks.

This is more complex, yes, but the current hidden complexity is worse.
Important part is that the UI should not dump the whole model on normal users
at once.

Probably the right shape is:

- simple default editing flow
- blocks / composition visible as a more explicit advanced structure

What I do *not* want is to keep calling these things "characters" when they are
really scenario/subvariant definitions.
